summary: Denise Lewis, an Olympic gold medalist, is married to Steve Finan O'Connor, the son of a well-known comedian and game show host. Lewis, who competed on "Strictly Come Dancing" and now commentates for the BBC, was moved to tears during the Olympics when Keely Hodgkinson won gold in the 800m. She is a mother to two children and her husband is a businessman. Team GB has recognized the contributions of mothers in the Olympics, and Lewis's family life is kept private. The athlete has spoken about the challenges of balancing her career and family, and credits her husband for his support.

name: Shamima Begum
summary: Shamima Begum, a British woman who fled to join the Islamic State group in Syria in 2015, has exhausted her legal options to regain her UK citizenship. The UK Supreme Court has refused to hear her appeal against the government's decision to strip her of her citizenship, a move that has been widely criticized as "profoundly wrong" by human rights organizations. Begum is currently living in a Syrian detention camp and has expressed a desire to return to the UK, but the government has maintained that she poses a security risk. Begum's legal team has indicated that they will now take her case to the European Court of Human Rights.

name: Brighton riots
summary: Brighton city center businesses have taken precautions by boarding up amid reports of potential race riots. Sussex Police is on standby for unrest as a counter-demonstration is planned. Politicians have condemned potential rioters, calling them unwelcome in Sussex. The Brighton Pride parade has excluded the Coca-Cola float, raising concerns. Despite concerns about far-right violence, thousands have gathered in Brighton to protect the city from a small group of protesters, with many restaurants closing early out of caution. A lone individual was isolated by police during a Brighton protest as hundreds lined the streets to show their support. The reasons for the UK-wide riots are still under investigation. Two health centers in Sussex have announced early closures due to riot concerns.

name: Angelman syndrome
summary: Colin Farrell has established a foundation in honor of his son, James, who has Angelman syndrome, a rare genetic disorder. Farrell has spoken openly about their journey, raising awareness about the condition and its impact on families. Angelman syndrome is characterized by developmental delays, speech impairments, and distinctive physical features. While there is no cure, recent trials of ION582 have shown promising results in easing symptoms. Farrell's son has inspired him to create a foundation that supports research, provides resources to families, and promotes inclusivity for individuals with Angelman syndrome. Through his foundation and personal experiences, Farrell aims to empower families affected by the disorder and foster a greater understanding of its complexities.

name: Skateboarding Olympics
summary: In the skateboarding competitions at the Paris 2024 Olympics, Team GB's Sky Brown, despite suffering a shoulder dislocation, has been cleared to participate. Australian Keegan Palmer successfully defended his Olympic skateboarding title. The BBC will broadcast the Women's Park Final live, featuring Sky Brown. The relationship between skateboarding and the Olympics remains complex. Arisa Trew, a 14-year-old, made history by winning Olympic gold in the skateboarding event. Sky Brown won a bronze medal for Team GB despite her injury. Keegan Palmer showcased both his skills and sportsmanship in winning his second Olympic gold medal. Brown and Trew, along with Hiraki Cocona, are young skateboarding stars who are pushing the boundaries of the sport at the Olympics.
